04184nam a22006375i 9781646020140DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97816460201407 a10.1515/97816460201402doi  a(DE-B1597)584294  a(OCoLC)1269268843  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0020002bisacsh1 aGeorge, A. R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOld Babylonian Texts in the Schøyen Collection, Part Two :bSchool Letters, Model Contracts, and Related Texts /cA. R. George, Gabriella Spada. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b64 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCUSAS: Cornell University Studies in Assyriology and Sumerology ;v4300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tStatement of Provenance -- tSeries Editor’s Preface -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tCatalog of Tablets -- tConcordances -- t1. Old Babylonian School Letters -- t2. Old Babylonian Model Contracts and Related Texts -- t3. Other Old Babylonian Legal Academic Texts -- tReferences -- tCuneiform Texts -- tCornell University Studies in Assyriology and Sumerology0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn ancient Mesopotamia, men training to be scribes copied model letters in order to practice writing and familiarize themselves with epistolary forms and expressions. Similarly, model contracts were used to teach them how to draw up agreements for the transactions typical of everyday economic life. This volume makes available a trove of previously unknown tablets and fragments, now housed in the Shøyen Collection, that were produced in the training of scribes in Old Babylonian schools.Following on Old Babylonian Texts in the Schøyen Collection, Part One: Selected Letters, this volume publishes the contents of sixty-five tablets bearing Akkadian letters used to train scribes and twenty-six prisms and tablets carrying Sumerian legal texts copied in the same context. Each text is presented in transliterated form and in translation, with appropriate commentary and annotations and, at the end of the book, photographs of the cuneiform. The material is made easily navigable by a catalogue, bibliography, and indexes.This collection of previously unknown documents expands the extant corpus of educational texts, making an essential contribution to the study of the ancient world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aGeorge, A. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOwen, David I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchøyen, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpada, Gabriella, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSpada, Gabriella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978164602014040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781646020140423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781646020140/original  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK